{"ticker": "PLTR", "company": "PALANTIR TECHNOLOGIES INC-A", "weight_sum": 18.799999999999997, "etfs": ["ARKK", "ARKF", "ARKQ", "ARKX", "ARKW"], "is_private": false, "query": "($PLTR OR \"Palantir Technologies\") -is:retweet min_faves:10 since_time:1777626311 until_time:1777633511", "n_fetched": 8, "n_kept": 1, "n_dropped": 7, "kept": [{"type": "tweet", "id": "2050151787596849178", "url": "https://x.com/MikeLongTerm/status/2050151787596849178", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/MikeLongTerm/status/2050151787596849178", "text": "$PLTR & National Health Serivce UK Deployment\n\nThe National Health Service (NHS) in England has long grappled with one of the most formidable operational challenges in modern healthcare: fragmented data systems. Serving approximately 57 million patients with 1.5 million staff across hundreds of hospital trusts, the NHS has historically relied on decades-old legacy infrastructure where critical information patient records, waiting lists, operating theatre schedules, and discharge plans existed in silos. A recent promotional article from Palantir Technologies, published on LinkedIn on April 30, 2026, titled \u201cReady, Set, Build with the NHS Federated Data Platform,\u201d presents the NHS Federated Data Platform (FDP) as a bold solution to this fragmentation. Delivered through a consortium led by Palantir on its Foundry platform, the FDP aims to connect data safely, enable actionable insights, and foster innovation. While the article highlights measurable impacts and grassroots development, a fuller analysis reveals both genuine potential and significant hurdles in adoption, ethics, and long-term sustainability.\n\nAt its core, the FDP employs a federated architecture that respects local control while enabling system-wide interoperability. Each NHS organization operates its own \u201ctenant,\u201d maintaining data controller status, with information remaining under local governance. A shared Canonical Data Model standardizes representations of data, logic, actions, and security policies, allowing nationally developed tools (for waiting list validation, discharge coordination, and theatre scheduling) to function alongside locally built applications. Privacy safeguards including encryption, purpose-based access, and Privacy Enhancing Technologies for de-identification are emphasized as foundational. This design theoretically balances the need for integration with data protection requirements, addressing decades of failed centralization attempts in the NHS.\n\nTrusts using the platform reportedly enabled 110,078 additional theatre procedures, safely removed 797,728 patients from waiting lists, facilitated 297,943 discharges with around a 15% reduction in delays, and improved 28-day cancer referral responses by 6.8%. These figures, if sustained and verified, represent meaningful relief for patients and staff amid chronic NHS pressures. Beyond core products, the platform\u2019s extensibility was showcased in the inaugural \u201cBuild with FDP\u201d 48-hour hackathon, where over 120 NHS developers, analysts, clinicians, and operational staff created 25 prototypes. Examples include an early warning system for patient deterioration, bed demand prediction tools, CAMHS workflow balancers, and genomic-optimized waitlist recommendations. Such events underscore a vision of clinician-led innovation scaling nationally through a common infrastructure. \n\nYet the FDP\u2019s rollout has not been seamless. Independent reporting indicates slower-than-expected adoption, with fewer than a quarter of England\u2019s roughly 215 hospital trusts actively using the platform by late 2024, rising to around one-third by mid-2025 in some accounts. Implementation costs for individual trusts\u2014requiring additional developers, project managers, and integration work\u2014have drawn criticism, as have assessments from some NHS insiders that the software itself is \u201cnot very good.\u201d These practical challenges highlight the gap between promotional narratives and on-the-ground realities in a vast, decentralized system.\n\nMore contentious are the ethical and political dimensions surrounding Palantir\u2019s central role. The U.S. firm\u2019s background in defense, intelligence, and controversial applications (such as immigration enforcement) has fueled opposition from the British Medical Association, unions, human rights organizations, and patient groups. Critics argue that awarding a \u00a3330 million-plus contract (with total costs potentially higher) to a foreign company with intelligence ties risks patient trust, data sovereignty, and long-term vendor lock-in. Palantir maintains strict contractual limits\u2014no commercialization of NHS data, no use for training external models\u2014and NHS England stresses that intellectual property arrangements protect public interests. Nevertheless, calls persist for reduced engagement or an eventual exit, reflecting deeper unease about outsourcing sensitive health infrastructure.\n\nThe FDP exemplifies broader tensions in public sector digital transformation. On one hand, leveraging commercial platforms like Foundry offers speed and sophistication that in-house development might struggle to match, especially given historical NHS IT shortcomings. The ontology-driven approach and federated model represent thoughtful engineering for a complex national system. On the other, heavy reliance on a single vendor raises questions of dependency, cost-effectiveness, and public accountability. The hackathon\u2019s emphasis on local problem-solving is encouraging, but its success will ultimately depend on whether prototypes translate into scalable, maintainable tools without entrenching external control.\n\nPalantir paints an optimistic picture of the NHS FDP as a platform that not only connects data but empowers action and innovation. Early metrics suggest real benefits for patients through reduced waits and better operational flow. However, modest adoption rates, implementation frictions, and intense ethical debates indicate that the platform\u2019s full potential remains contested. For the NHS a cherished institution serving an entire nation the FDP\u2019s ultimate value will be measured not by promotional claims or hackathon prototypes, but by sustained improvements in care delivery, robust safeguards for patient data, and the ability to evolve independently over time. As the next \u201cBuild with FDP\u201d events unfold, the initiative stands as both a test of technological ambition and a mirror to the UK\u2019s ongoing struggle to modernize its health service without compromising its founding principles.\n\nSource: https://t.co/qfaOE6y8hb", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 0, "replyCount": 0, "likeCount": 14, "quoteCount": 0, "viewCount": 847, "createdAt": "Fri May 01 09:54:10 +0000 2026", "lang": "en", "bookmarkCount": 2, "isReply": false, "inReplyToId": null, "conversationId": "2050151787596849178", "displayTextRange": [0, 280], "inReplyToUserId": null, "inReplyToUsername": null, "author": {"type": "user", "userName": "MikeLongTerm", "url": "https://x.com/MikeLongTerm", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/MikeLongTerm", "id": "1280587925336530948", "name": "Mike", "isVerified": false, "isBlueVerified": true, "verifiedType": null, "profilePicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1532356424453480448/hGjaGQoQ_normal.jpg", "coverPicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_banners/1280587925336530948/1694632431", "description": "", "location": "Tweets AREN'T Financial Advice", "followers": 23550, "following": 392, "status": "", "canDm": false, "canMediaTag": true, "createdAt": "Tue Jul 07 19:42:13 +0000 2020", "entities": {"description": {"urls": []}, "url": {}}, "fastFollowersCount": 0, "favouritesCount": 9339, "hasCustomTimelines": true, "isTranslator": false, "mediaCount": 8589, "statusesCount": 28248, "withheldInCountries": [], "affiliatesHighlightedLabel": {}, "possiblySensitive": false, "pinnedT